title: Institutional Press Policies (Mississippi Gulf Coast Community College)

communications.subject: Mississippi Public Records Act Request: Institutional Press Policies (Mississippi Gulf Coast Community College)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Mississippi Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Any policy, guidance, handbook, manual, or standard contract concerning the institution’s interactions or relationship with members of the news media, reporters, or journalists, including student journalists. 

2. Any policy, guidance, handbook, or manual concerning the interactions or communications of institutional employees, including faculty, administrators, staff, and student employees, with the news media, reporters, or journalists, including student journalists. 

Please note that this request does not seek a search of faculty or student email accounts or records. These requests should in no way be construed to include a review or search of email accounts, websites, or other forms of data or document retention which are controlled by students, alumni, or faculty members, nor by governmental or advisory bodies controlled by the same, except insofar as any such individuals also serve in an administrative capacity and the records were created or are held by the individual in that capacity. Any search should be limited to documents held by the administration and/or its staff members, including records created or maintained by persons acting in the capacity of administrators or staff members.

This request is made on behalf of the Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression, a nonprofit and nonpartisan organization that aims to defend and sustain the individual rights of all Americans to free speech and free thought. This request concerns a matter of public interest. The records are sought for the purpose of researching and educating the public about policies affecting student journalists' ability to engage in news gathering and reporting on college and university campuses.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Anne Marie Tamburro

communications.communication: I have not received a response to this public records request within the five days as provided by law, when might I expect a response?

communications.subject: RE: Fax Received from CSID: +17249461484  -  Pages received: 2
communications.communication:
Mr. Keplar,

In response to your November 1, 2023 public records request for:

"All key performance indicators (KPIs) tracked within the school district including but not limited to all KPIs related to the EPS Strategic Plan Strategic Plan."

The District's Strategic Plan is linked here<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1i_528CnYIBjEvcYlYpc7EjTVkDTv7eqZ/view>. The District spent the previous year solidifying the goals, metrics and outcomes of the Strategic Plan. It's my understanding the focus this year is to identify KPIs. This means the District does not currently have any records responsive to your request.

If you should have any questions or concerns at all about any aspect of our processing of your public records request, please let me know. Still while welcoming such contact by you, the Public Records Act advises I should notify you that, by my delivery of this email to you, our School District considers your request closed. So please know that we do now consider your request as having been closed.

Thank you,

Eliza Cornelison
Paralegal | Human Resources
Evergreen Public Schools
360-604-4049 | eliza.cornelison@evergreenps.org<mailto:eliza.cornelison@evergreenps.org>

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Conficker - FBI
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Investigative records FBI may be holding on the "Conficker" (Also refered to as 'downadup', 'downup' or 'kido') worm from 2008. This worm impacted hundreds of thousands of internet hosts when it was first released, and continues to impact internet services even today.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emily Crose

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1450436-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@ic.fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 138 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 571 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,289 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 1,649 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
F: (540) 868-4391
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

title: Bruceville Eddy, Texas Police Department Chief Dorsey

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Bruceville Eddy, Texas Police Department Chief Dorsey
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Copy of letter or notes, or emails from a Jan Grice, James Grice, James R. Grice or "Jan" Grice, or Jan G. Copies also of the envelope. All results of closed investigation into identity of "Jan Grice". Copies of ALL Jan or Jan G letters to all City Council members and Mayor. Copy of file from already resolved so thereby Open Records the Unemployment Hearing notes, letters, files, audio tapes, and video tapes from termination of Justin Richardson. Any reference to Bernadette or Berni Feazell in any correspondence concerning said firing, or reprimand.  Emails, letters, notes from converences, or audio tapes of any meetings between Chief Dorsey and Chris Eubanks, this includes phone calls about Berni Feazell and/or Justin Richardson. Any in person meetings?  Letters to the Bruceville Police department from Justin Richardson, or to Justin Richardson, and/or about Justin Richardson. Receipts of any meetings between Chief Dorsey, or any officer and Chris Eubank in person. Any and all meetings with City Attorney or City Manager about firing Justin Richardson for his blog or hanging out with Bernadette Feazell. Any investigation into Bernadette Feazell, including ordering of criminal records, or asking Chris Eubank or anyone in Law Enforcement. Thank you

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Bernadette Feazell

Open Records Request Received on 10/26/2023.
Current Status of Request: Further Response Coming.

title: ICE Public Affairs Responses to In-Custody Deaths at Aurora, Torrance

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: ICE Public Affairs Responses to In-Custody Deaths at Aurora, Torrance
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

On behalf of the Al Otro Lado #DetentionKills Transparency Initiative, we respectfully request all records created or received by ICE's Office of Public Affairs at the Headquarters, El Paso Field Office, and Denver Field Office levels regarding the deaths in custody of Kesley Dial at CoreCivic's Torrance, New Mexico facility and The GEO Group's Aurora, Colorado facility. Specifically, we seek emails sent or received, calendar entries for appointments to discuss either of the deaths in custody, Teams messages, the contents of SharePoint drive folders regarding ICE's public statements regarding these deaths, and any records relied upon to assert the factual matters in ICE's post-death release statements, posted here: 
https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/brazilian-man-ice-custody-passes-away-new-mexico-hospital?s=09
and here: 
https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/nicaraguan-man-ice-custody-passes-away-colorado-hospital

By definition, the information requested cannot be subject to withholding under Exemption 7A (open investigations), because ICE has already released its core facts publicly.

We seek expedited processing of this request under 6 C.F.R. 5.5(e), and make the following statements under penalty of perjury pursuant to 28 USC 1746 in support thereof: 
1. Both the Torrance in-custody death and the Aurora in-custody death have been met with calls from elected Representatives and Senators for vigorous investigation, based on each facility's documented track record. See https://www.heinrich.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/heinrich-leads-request-for-immediate-action-from-ice-to-address-inhumane-unsafe-conditions-for-migrants-at-the-torrance-county-detention-facility and https://crow.house.gov/sites/evo-subsites/crow.house.gov/files/evo-media-document/2022.10.21-final-icedhs-letter_0.pdf. 

2. Both deaths have been the subject of widespread and sustained media attention. 
For Torrance: 
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/09/22/us/politics/aclu-ice-immigration-detention.html
https://sourcenm.com/2022/09/01/brazilian-asylum-seeker-who-died-by-suicide-held-in-horrific-conditions-attorneys-say/
https://nmpoliticalreport.com/2022/08/31/immigrant-advocacy-organizations-seeking-answers-around-brazilian-mans-death-by-suicide-while-in-ice-custody/
https://www.democracynow.org/2022/10/18/headlines/asylum_seekers_at_torrance_ice_jail_claim_retaliation_over_hunger_strike
https://theappeal.org/torrance-detention-center-kesley-vial-brazil/
https://www.santafenewmexican.com/opinion/letters_to_editor/close-torrance-county-ice-facility-now/article_08a7cf58-5705-11ed-b432-1bb650ab5a32.html
https://www.krqe.com/news/crime/man-commits-suicide-in-ice-custody-in-torrance-county/
https://www.democracynow.org/2022/8/29/headlines/asylum_seeker_dies_by_suicide_at_for_profit_ice_jail_in_new_mexico
https://www.abqjournal.com/2528527/webhedline-126.html
https://www.lcsun-news.com/story/news/local/new-mexico/2022/09/30/groups-retaliation-after-migrants-report-torrance-county-detention-center/69530415007/

For Aurora: 
https://www.cpr.org/2022/10/27/colorado-lawmakers-call-for-investigation-into-death-at-aurora-ice-facility/
https://www.cpr.org/2022/11/03/advocates-immigration-customs-enforcement-custody-death/
https://www.9news.com/article/news/local/man-nicaragua-dies-aurora-ice-facility/73-f52d0d45-531c-4e17-a361-1376d887e499
https://www.denver7.com/news/local-news/colorado-lawmakers-call-for-probe-after-detainees-death-at-aurora-ice-facility
https://www.cbsnews.com/colorado/news/melvin-ariel-calero-mendoza-nicaraguan-father-dies-ice-custody-aurora-facility/
https://www.longmontleader.com/local-news/el-comite-wants-answers-to-ice-detention-death-5990654
https://news.yahoo.com/video/nicaraguan-father-two-dies-ice-040542382.html
https://www.newsbreak.com/news/2810691040469/report-details-what-led-up-to-man-s-death-in-aurora-ice-custody

3. In both cases, serious questions have been raised by elected officials as to the circumstances surrounding each person's death, and ICE and its contractors' compliance with mandatory duties surrounding care of detained immigrants. 

Therefore, the requirements of 6 C.F.R. 5.5(e) are satisfied, and expedited processing is proper. 

Thank you for your prompt attention to this important request, and your response within the statutorily required 10-calendar day period! 

#DetentionKills Transparency Initiative
Al Otro Lado

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

communications.subject: RE: ICE FOIA Case Number 2023-ICFO-03462
communications.communication:
12/21/2022Andrew FreeMuckRock News, DEPT MR136588Boston, Massachusetts 02115RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2023-ICFO-03462        Dear Requester:This acknowledges receipt of your 11/8/2022, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for all records created or received by ICE's Office of Public Affairs at the Headquarters, El Paso Field Office, and Denver Field Office levels regarding the deaths in custody of Kesley Dial at CoreCivic's Torrance, New Mexico facility and The GEO Group's Aurora, Colorado facility. .  Your request was received in this office on 11/8/2022.After careful review of your FOIA request, we determined that your request is 1) too broad in scope, 2) did not specifically identify the records which you are seeking, or 3) only posed questions to the agency.  Records must be described in reasonably sufficient detail to enable government employees who are familiar with the subject area to locate records without placing an unreasonable burden upon the agency.  For this reason, §5.3(b) of the DHS regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, require that you describe the records you are seeking with as much information as possible to ensure that our search can locate them with a reasonable amount of effort.  Whenever possible, a request should include specific information about each record sought, such as the date, title or name, author, recipients, and subject matter of the records, if known, or the ICE program office you believe created and/or controls the record.  The FOIA does not require an agency to create new records, answer questions posed by requesters, or attempt to interpret a request that does not identify specific records.  Please resubmit your request containing a reasonable description of the records you are seeking.  Upon receipt of a perfected request, you will be advised as to the status of your request.If we do not hear from you within 30 days from the date of this letter, we will assume you are no longer interested in this FOIA request, and the case will be administratively closed.  Please be advised that this action is not a denial of your request and will not preclude you from filing other requests in the future. If you have any questions please contact FOIA Public Liaison Marcus Francis at (866) 633-1182 or the address above.Your request has been assigned reference number 2023-ICFO-03462. Sincerely,ICE-FOIA

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2023-ICFO-03462
communications.communication:
We appeal the agency’s determination that the request is improper. 

It seeks:

“emails sent or received, calendar entries for appointments to discuss either of the deaths in custody, Teams messages, the contents of SharePoint drive folders regarding ICE's public statements regarding these deaths, and any records relied upon to assert the factual matters in ICE's post-death release statements, posted [on ICE’s website].”

We seek expedited processing of this request for the reasons described in our original submission. 

#DetentionKills Transparency Initiative 
Al Otro Lado

title: Request for ZEEVIC Work Group Meeting Records

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Request for ZEEVIC Work Group Meeting Records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am seeking access to records related to the Zero Emission Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Council (ZEEVIC) Work Group meetings held since July 1, 2023. These records include agendas, lists of attendees, and meeting notes as well as any other related records. I am interested in records from both the ZEV Policy Scorecard Work Group and the Trucking MHDV Infrastructure Work Group meetings, as well as any other ZEEVIC Work Group meetings that have been held. I am also seeking any records announcing the Work Group meetings as well as any communications inviting attendees or potential attendees. 

If all or any part of this request is denied, I request that I be provided with a written explanation that includes the reason for the denial, the legal authority justifying the denial, and my appeal rights. If you determine that some portions of the requested records are exempt from disclosure, please provide me with the portions that can be disclosed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Lanny Hartmann

communications.subject: RE: Maryland Public Information Act Request #854784
communications.communication:
Thank you for your prompt response to my Public Information Act (PIA) request and for providing me with the estimated cost for fulfilling the original request. In light of the associated cost and to expedite the process, I would like to refine my request as follows:

I am now specifically interested in obtaining information related to the Zero Emission Vehicle (ZEV) Policy Scorecard working group and the Trucking Medium and Heavy-Duty Vehicle (MHDV) Infrastructure working group. More specifically, I am seeking a list of the ZEEVIC members appointed to each of these working groups by the Chair, as prescribed in the ZEEVIC Procedures.

Given the nature of this more targeted request, I believe it will take less than two hours of work to fulfill. Therefore, I anticipate that there should be no additional cost associated with this revised request.

I appreciate your attention to this matter and look forward to receiving the revised information at your earliest convenience.

Sincerely,

Lanny Hartmann

title: Washington Public Records Act Request: Tuberculosis case notification data and related policies, 2000-2022

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Washington Public Records Act Request: Tuberculosis case notification data and related policies, 2000-2022
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:


*  Records of TB case notifications in all Washington state prisons, with day and institution of notification for each case from January 2020-July 2022.
* Records of date of TB treatment initiation for all notified cases.
* Records ofTB treatment outcomes for all notified cases. 
* Records of number of and location of incarcerated individuals offered TB testing and number of individuals who were tested and date of testing.
* Records of TB case notifications in all Washington state prisons for corrections officers in all WA state prisons, with day and institution of notification for each case from January 2020-July 2022.
* Records of number of and location of corrections officers offered TB testing and number of individuals who were tested.
* Any and all WDOC policies and procedures regarding TB prevention and control measures put in place in prisons.
* Records of movements of incarcerated individuals from or to any of the prisons reporting TB cases from January 2020-July 2022, including the number of individuals transferred, date of transfer, reason of transfer, origin prison, and destination prison.

For all items, we are requesting de-identified records.


The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. Further, we respectfully request a waiver of these fees as we are affiliated with a research institution, and this request is made for a scholarly or scientific purpose and not for a commercial use. We would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Katharine Walter

You state your request to be for the following records:

1.      Records of TB case notifications in all Washington state prisons, with day and institution of notification for each case from January 2020‐July 2022
2.      Records of date of TB treatment initiation for all notified cases
3.      Records of TB treatment outcomes for all notified cases
4.      Records of number of and location of incarcerated individuals offered TB testing and number of individuals who were tested and date of testing
5.      Records of TB case notifications in all Washington state prisons for corrections officers in all WA state prisons, with day and institution of notification for each case from January 2020‐July 2022
6.      Records of number of and location of corrections officers offered TB testing and number of individuals who were tested
7.      Any and all WDOC policies and procedures regarding TB prevention and control measures put in place in prisons
8.      Records of movements of incarcerated individuals from or to any of the prisons reporting TB cases from January 2020‐July 2022, including the number of individuals transferred, date of transfer, reason of transfer, origin prison, and destination prison

I interpret your request to be for disclosure of the following records:

1.      Records showing TB case notifications from the time frame of January 1, 2020, to July 19, 2022 (the date your request was received) in all Washington state prisons, including date and facility location
2.      Records showing date of TB treatment initiation for all notified cases
3.      Records showing all TB treatment outcomes for all notified cases
4.      Records showing number of, and facility location of incarcerated individuals offered TB testing including number of individuals who were tested and date of testing
5.      Records showing TB case notifications from the time frame of January 1, 2020, to July 19, 2022 (the date your request was received) in all Washington state prisons for corrections officers in all Washington state prisons, including date and facility location
6.      Records showing number of, and facility location of corrections officers offered TB testing and number of individuals who were tested
7.      Any and all current g Washington State Department of Corrections policies and procedures regarding TB prevention and control measures put in place in prisons
8.      Records showing movements of incarcerated individuals from or to any of the prison facilities reporting TB cases during the time frame of January 1, 2020 to July 19 2022, (the date your request was received) including the number of individuals transferred, date of transfer, reason for transfer, origin facility, and receiving facility

Sincerely,

Tonja Monroe, Public Records Specialist

communications.communication:
Dear Tanja,

Thank you for your help with this request and we look forward to the complete data. 

In response to your email about item 1 in our record request, we understand that you are not able to provide individual records. To understand the epidemiology of the outbreak though, information on location of cases is essential. Would it be possible to include the de-identified number of cases and dates of case notifications per facility (item #1) as is routinely done for COVID-19 in Washington prisons? 

Thank you again for your time.

Sincerely,
Katharine Walter

communications.subject: Public Records Request P-29139, Installment 4
communications.communication:
Ms. Walter:

This e-mail is in follow-up to my last correspondence to you, dated January 19, 2023, regarding your public records request, P-29139.  You requested the following records:

1.      Records showing TB case notifications from the time frame of January 1, 2020, to July 19, 2022 (the date your request was received) in all Washington state prisons, including date and facility location
2.      Records showing date of TB treatment initiation for all notified cases
3.      Records showing all TB treatment outcomes for all notified cases
4.      Records showing number of, and facility location of incarcerated individuals offered TB testing including number of individuals who were tested and date of testing
5.      Records showing TB case notifications from the time frame of January 1, 2020, to July 19, 2022 (the date your request was received) in all Washington state prisons for corrections officers in all Washington state prisons, including date and facility location
6.      Records showing number of, and facility location of corrections officers offered TB testing and number of individuals who were tested
7.      Any and all current Washington State Department of Corrections policies and procedures regarding TB prevention and control measures put in place in prisons
8.      Records showing movements of incarcerated individuals from or to any of the prison facilities reporting TB cases during the time frame of January 1, 2020, to July 19 2022, (the date your request was received) including the number of individuals transferred, date of transfer, reason for transfer, origin facility, and receiving facility

I have attached a 4th and final installment of records (2 pages) consisting of records responsive to items 5 & 6 of your request. These documents are provided to you in accordance with the Public Records Act.  By providing you these documents and/or information, the Department is not responsible for your use of this information or for any claims or liabilities that may result from your use or further dissemination.

The file for P-29139 is now closed.  If you should have any questions related to this request, you may contact me at tonja.monroe@doc1.wa.gov<mailto:tonja.monroe@doc1.wa.gov>.

Sincerely,

Tonja Monroe
Public Records Specialist
Department of Corrections | Public Records Unit
P.O. Box 41118 | Olympia, WA  98504-1118

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #P-29139
communications.communication:
Dear all,

Thank you for your latest installment. Would you please clarify what the two tables (items 5 and 6) include? Is item 5 the number of positive skin tests among correctional officers? Were these unique tests or unique individuals? If the former, would you please indicate as well the number of individuals who had been ever tested and the number of individuals who had at least one positive skin test? 

For item 6, is this the number of individuals tested? Would you please stratify this by time period so that we can determine rate of skin test positivity? 

Thank you for your help. We look forward to your response. 

Sincerely,
Katharine Walter

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #P-29139
communications.communication:
Ms. Walter,
I am emailing in response to your correspondence dated November 3, 2023. You ask for clarification on the tables sent in response to items 5 and 6 of your public records request P-29139.
Table 5 shows TB case notifications for corrections officers from the time frame of January 1, 2020, to July 19, 2022, in all Washington state prisons.
Table 6 shows TB tests given to all staff at facilities during the time frame of January 1, 2020, to July 19, 2022.
If you should have any additional questions related to this request, you may contact me at tonja.monroe@doc1.wa.gov<mailto:tonja.monroe@doc1.wa.gov>.

Sincerely,

Tonja Monroe
Public Records Specialist
Department of Corrections | Public Records Unit
P.O. Box 41118 | Olympia, WA  98504-1118

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Heather Johnston Death - Police (Gwinnett County Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records, reports, body cam footage and other audio or video recordings related to the death of Heather Faye Besco Johnston. Mrs. Johnston died on or around July 3, 2021.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Cole Howard

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Daniel Ellsberg
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry into former U.S. military analyst Daniel Ellsberg (April 7, 1931 – June 16, 2023). His death is widely-known and has been widely reported, privacy concerns under FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7 are voided, as are any concerns under the Privacy Act. You may find an obituary from NBC News attached below, and a statement by Mr. Ellsberg's son at the following link: https://twitter.com/RobertEllsberg/status/1669776046751899648

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records of both HQ and all field offices for all relevant names, agencies, organizations, companies and events including but not limited to those cited in the previous paragraphs and/or links as well as a cross-reference with the Southern Poverty Law Center to include any information provided by the SPLC. My request includes but is not limited to 137, 157, 176, 177, 183, 184, 188, and 214 files.

If any part of these documents are exempt from disclosure, please be sure to review and release all reasonably segregable nonexempt portions of responsive documents, as the FOIA requires

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Petti

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1596242-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for this partial response. In your letter, you write:

"Please be advised that additional records responsive to your subject exist. If this release of previously processed material does not satisfy your request, you must advise us that you want the additional records processed."

I would like to formally advise that I would like the additional records processed. Please confirm receipt of my request. Thank you again for your prompt attention to this matter.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Daniel Ellsberg
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of any FBI files on Daniel Ellsberg. Born April 7, 1931 in Chicago, Illinois, Daniel Ellsberg died June 16, 2023 in Kensington, California. He was America's most famous whistleblower. His death at age 92 was widely reported in the media in June, 2023. He was the husband of the American journalist Patricia Marx Ellsberg. He is also known by the name Dan Ellsberg.

Records relating to or mentioning Daniel Ellsberg. Major media outlets across America as of June 16th, 2023 have reported his death including: https://www.washingtonpost.com/obituaries/2023/06/16/daniel-ellsberg-pentagon-papers-dead/ https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/16/us/daniel-ellsberg-dead.html

Please conduct searches of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the SENTINEL system, FBI email system, the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Records System, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, Counter-drug Information Indices System (CIIS), Investigative Data Warehouse (IDW) including but not limited to Investigative Data Warehouse - Secret, IDW-S Core, SPT, and DOCLAB-S, FBI Automated Case Support system (ACS), subset of the Electronic Case File (ECF) system, National Crime Information Center (NCIC), Combined DNA Index System (CODIS), Integrated Automated Fingerprint Identification System (IAFIS), Interstate Photo System (IPS) and/or Facial Recognition Databases such as those used by FACE (Facial Analysis, Comparison, and Evaluation) specialists, and the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA) warrant applications and/or Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court (FISC) record filings, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. Please further consult all available cross-reference indices, databases, and records, in addition to any other data sources containing potentially-responsive materials related to Daniel Ellsberg.

Please include all potentially responsive materials, including but not limited to all communications, reports, investigations, inquiries, audio files, photographs or image files, video files, memos, email systems, directives, network packet captures, meeting minute notes, calendar entries, and any other data or data format that is used by the FBI. Please include all materials found in other subject files and all materials associated with any potentially-related names and any other known aliases, code names, nicknames, or any other identifying pseudonyms or references utilized by this agency or any other agency that is known to the FBI. Please additionally include searches for inter-agency or non-agency communications accessible by the FBI about Daniel Ellsberg.

If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

It is my understanding that your agency is required to search the records stored at NARA’s Washington Records Center in Suitland, MD, which remain technically under your agency’s control (see 36 CFR 1250.8). Please also conduct a search of records at NARA's Washington Records Center in Suitland, for records related to Daniel Ellsberg.

Furthermore, I request the FOIA log and copies of all other requests for information on Daniel Ellsberg including the responsive documents.

Daniel Ellsberg was a public figure. This request is a critical part of a journalistic research project which requires the responsive documents for informing the public.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jacob Appelbaum

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1596215-000
communications.communication:
Hello,

I am writing to follow up on recent communication regarding my FOIA request regarding Dr. Daniel Ellsberg.

Thank you for sending copies of previously released information about Dr. Daniel Ellsberg in partial fulfillment of FOIPA Request No.: 1596215-000. I see that in the reply that contains these previously released documents, additional records that are responsive to my request exist. I am writing to confirm within the allotted thirty day window that this material does not satisfy my request as most of the documents are more than forty years old, and many are much older. I understand that Dr. Daniel Ellsberg continued to be of interest to the FBI long after the early 1980s. I request that the additional records about my requested subject be processed.

Thank you for your time and assistance in this matter.

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1596215-000
communications.communication:
The FBI has received your additional correspondence regarding your Freedom of Information/Privacy Act (FOIPA) request and it has been forwarded to the assigned analyst for review and determination.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Military Service Record
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A releasable copy of the Official Military Personnel File of Joseph "Joe" Patrick Quinn, date of birth March 14, 1980, which should include: Name, Service Number, Dates of Service, Branch of Service, Final Duty Status, Final Rank, Assignments and Geographical locations, Military Education Level, Awards and Decorations, Photograph, Transcripts of Courts-Martial Trial, and place of entrance and separation

I would also like a releasable copy of his Official Personnel Folder which should include: past and present positions, past and present titles, past and present salaries, past and present grades, past and present job locations

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

George Johnston
An acknowledgement letter, stating the request is being processed.

If you are having difficulty accessing your response document(s), please try the basic troubleshooting tips below:

- Password: Enter your request number (including the dash symbol).

- Unable to locate documents: Enter the information EXACTLY as it was provided in the original request. A ZIP code OR phone number (last four) is required.  Use the ZIP code OR phone number provided in the original request; otherwise, your response will not be located.  

- 30-day expiration: For security reasons, response documents are not accessible after 30 days and a new request will need to be submitted. Requests may be created using our online ordering system at: https://vetrecs.archives.gov/VeteranRequest/home.html

- No computer/laptop/printer: Suggest using resources (public library, family/friends, etc.) to access the eDelivery portal and download your documents. The eDelivery portal is also accessible via your mobile device. Be sure to fully remove downloaded documents from non-personal devices.

If you have already tried the tips outlined above and still require assistance, contact our Customer Service Team at (314) 801-0800 and have your request information available.

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: District blocked domains
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

1) An activity log showing all web domains blocked by the district's web filter (such as Securly, GoGuardian, Lightspeed Systems, Gaggle, or other CIPA-compliant filters) from Jan. 1, 2022 until the date this request is processed. The log should be provided as a .csv or .xlsx file and should include all data fields available from the district's web filter provider (e.g. the domain, the school, the reason blocked, the date) with the exception of personally identifiable fields (e.g., name, email, IP address). To assist with your search, I've included instructions for downloading blocked domain activity logs from several popular web filter providers:

Instructions for obtaining Securly blocked activity logs:
https://support.securly.com/hc/en-us/articles/115013346088-How-is-user-activity-displayed-under-the-Reports-tab-

Instructions for obtaining GoGuardian blocked activity logs:
https://support.goguardian.com/s/article/Admin-Activity-Page-1630339933157

Instructions for obtaining Lightspeed Systems blocked activity logs:
https://www.lightspeedsystems.com/blog/lightspeed-filter-reports-with-web-activity-log/

2) An activity log showing all search terms blocked and/or flagged by the district's web filter from Jan. 1, 2022 until the date this request is processed. The log should be provided as a .csv or .xlsx file and should include all data fields available from the district's web filter provider (e.g. the flagged term, the school, the reason flagged, the date) with the exception of personally identifiable fields (e.g., name or IP address).

I ask that all fees be waived as I am a journalist and intend to use the requested records to publish articles in the public interest about the operations of a government agency. In the event you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employee involved and an explanation of the employee hours required to fulfill the request.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of responsive documents, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Open Records Request: Kral & ShotSpotter
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Metadata for email communications sent or received, including being CCed or BBCed, for former Police Chief George Kral and anyone with a ShotSpotter email address (*@shotspotter.com) between the dates of 1/1/2020 and 12/31/2022.

The specific metadata data points I'm interested in are: to address(es), from address, cc address(es), bcc address(es), sent date/time, received date/time, subject line, and if the email has an attachment. This request does not seek the contents of the emails themselves, and only the specified email metadata. As IL FOIA allows a requester to specify a file format, please provide me the records in an Excel format.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

e

communications.subject: Automatic reply: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Open Records Request: Kral & ShotSpotter
communications.communication:
YOUR PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST HAS BEEN SUBMITTED SUCCESSFULLY.

The Public Records Office processes requests for records that include bulk (three or more) Crime Reports,  911 Audio, Police Body Cam and Dash Cam Video, Photos, Policies and Procedures, and Personnel / Internal Affairs Records.  Some records are subject to fees and prepayment may be necessary.

If your submitted request is NOT for a bulk (three or more) report request or records outlined above, it will be routed to the Records Section for fulfillment via email TPDReportRequest@toledo.oh.gov.

More information on requesting crime and accident reports can be located on our website www.toledopolice.com.<http://www.toledopolice.com.>

Accident reports can be retrieved from the department website at no cost. Click HERE<https://tpdaccidentreports.noris.org> to be directed.

Please understand that we are working diligently to ensure your request is processed and fulfilled in a timely manner. We are unable to provide status updates.

Thank you for your patience.

Sincerely,

e

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: Challenge to A Court of Mist and Fury (Lexington & Richland Counties, SC)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

All records relating to the review of A Court of Mist and Fury in the 2023–2024 school year, including (but not limited to): any complaints about or challenges to the book and records of any discussions of the complaints, challenges, or review (before and after).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

M. Alan Thomas II

communications.subject: FOIA Request
communications.communication:
Hi Mr. Thomas-

School District Five of Lexington and Richland Counties has received your
Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request for the following documents:

   - All records relating to the review of A Court of Mist and Fury in the
   2023–2024 school year, including (but not limited to): any complaints about
   or challenges to the book and records of any discussions of the complaints,
   challenges, or review (before and after)

School District Five does possess existing documents and will make any
records responsive to this request available to you under the FOIA,
§30-4-30, subject to the exemption and redaction of records that are exempt
from disclosure pursuant to the FOIA, §§30-4-40(a)(2), (4), (5), and (7).
School District Five will produce this information within thirty (30) days
as required in the FOIA §30-4-30.

communications.subject: New Hampshire Right to Know Law Request: 10/9/22 colbee hodgman, Everett dam
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Hampshire Right to Know Law, I hereby request the following records:

My name is chiara cross, the best friend of Colbee Cammarata, Hodgman who died at the everett dam on 10/9/22. I was there with him along with my friend Emily. I called the police department a couple days after the incident asking for more details. I’m worried my brain has distorted some of the memory from that call and I’m looking to make sure I heard the phone call correctly..the police officer said someone was up there with him and that’s why he fell. Im look for clarity to make sure that’s correct. I have no means to hurt or go after anyone, I wanna make sure when I’m talking about it I’m saying the right thing.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Chiara Cross

Emma Best

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request: WFO 65-11613 refs (Ellsberg)
communications.communication:
Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@ic.fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 134 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 523 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,335 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 1,875 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
Record/Information Dissemination Section (RIDS) FBI-Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive, Winchester, VA 22602-4843
Direct: (540) 868-4593
Fax: (540) 868-4391
Questions E-mail: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Nevada Public Records Act Request: Jamba Juice inspection report
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Nevada Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All food establishment inspection reports for Jamba Juice located at 5140 Kietzke Ln, Reno, NV 89511 from January 2021-September 2023.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Evan Lake

title: FOIL Request for Information on COVID-19 Tests and Masks Distribution to Schools (New York State Education Department)

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: FOIL Request for Information on COVID-19 Tests and Masks Distribution to Schools (New York State Education Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. All communications between the Governor's Office and/or the State Education Department and/or Boards of Cooperative Educational Services (BOCES) regarding the distribution of COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks to schools, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.
  
2. Records of all requests submitted by school districts and BOCES for COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

3. Inventory records detailing the quantities of COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks that have been delivered to each BOCES for distribution to school districts, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

4. Any and all guidelines, memos, or advisories issued by the Governor's Office or the New York State Department of Health (DOH) regarding the distribution of COVID-19 rapid test kits and masks to schools, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jackson Parker

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: FOIL Request for Information on COVID-19 Tests and Masks Distribution to Schools (New York State Education Department)
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Parker:

This is to acknowledge receipt of your Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) request for State Education Department (SED) records regarding COVID-19 test kits and mask distribution.  The reference number for this request is FL-EM-23/1172.   Please be advised that you will hear further from the Department by approximately October 20, 2023 as to whether your request will be granted or denied in whole or in part.

SED charges the statutorily permitted fees under FOIL. These include $.25 per page for photocopies or the actual cost of reproducing records requested under FOIL (Public Officers Law §87[1][b][iii]). Payment must be made to the NYS Education Department by check or money order. Do not send any payment until you are notified that your request is granted and informed of the charge for your request. If your request is granted, the records will be provided to you in the manner requested (i.e. hardcopy or electronic), or if not specified, in a reasonable manner selected by this office.

If your request is granted, and there is a fee, one of the following will happen:

1. If your request can be filled immediately, and the total photocopy or reproduction fee is under $25.00, staff will forward the requested records to you with a statement what you owe. Or:

2. If the reproduction fee or photocopy fee for your request is $25.00 or more, you will be advised of the page count (+100 pages) or other expenses and the fee(s) owed in advance of our providing the records. Upon receipt of payment, staff will photocopy or otherwise reproduce the requested records and transmit, as appropriate. Or:

3. If it will take time to locate and/or photocopy or otherwise reproduce the records you have requested, you will be given a date by which you will be provided with a page count and/or estimated cost to fulfil your request.

Please note, there is no provision in law or regulation requiring the waiver of a fee under FOIL.
Regards,
Records Access Officer

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: FOIL Request for Information on COVID-19 Tests and Masks Distribution to Schools (New York State Education Department)
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Parker:

The following is in response to your FOIL request (FL-EM-23/1172) regarding:

1. All communications between the Governor's Office and/or the State Education Department and/or Boards of Cooperative Educational Services (BOCES) regarding the distribution of COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks to schools, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

2. Records of all requests submitted by school districts and BOCES for COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

3. Inventory records detailing the quantities of COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks that have been delivered to each BOCES for distribution to school districts, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

4. Any and all guidelines, memos, or advisories issued by the Governor's Office or the New York State Department of Health (DOH) regarding the distribution of COVID-19 rapid test kits and masks to schools, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.
received on September 18, 2023.

Your request is granted in part and denied in part.

Please find the responsive documents for part one attached.  Records were also redacted and withheld pursuant to Public Officers Law §87(2)(g), as inter/intra agency communications. After a review of such records, it was determined that they contain non-final communications which express opinion, advice, recommendations, and the like (see Public Officers Law §87[2][g][iii]).

In response to parts two through four, please be advised the State Education Department does not possess these records. The Freedom of Information Law does not require an agency to prepare any record not possessed or maintained by the agency (Public Officers Law Section 89[3][a]); therefore, those portions of your request are denied.

You may wish to contact the NYS Governor’s Office or the NYS Department of Health regarding those portions.

If you wish to appeal this response, you may do so within 30 days by emailing FOILappeal@nysed.gov<mailto:FOILappeal@nysed.gov> or writing to:

Betty A. Rosa
Commissioner of Education
NYS Education Department
Room 111, Education Building
89 Washington Avenue
Albany, NY  12234


Sincerely,
Records Access Officer

title: Water use by volume in Plaquemines Parish

communications.subject: Louisiana Public Records Law Request: Water use by volume in Plaquemines Parish
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Louisiana Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. Total volume water used in the Belle Chasse and Port Sulphur water districts for the following months:
May, June, July, August, and September 2020
May, June, July, August, and September 2021
May, June, July, August, and September 2022
May, June, July, August, and September 2023

2. All data regarding the 10 largest residential, commercial, and industrial users of water in the agency's West Bank districts since May 01 2023.

3. Venture Global's water use records by volume, indicating how many million gallons per day (MGD) used, or averages if daily volume records are unavailable, since May 01 2023.

4. Zachary Group's water use records by volume, indicating how many million gallons per day (MGD) used, or averages if daily volume records are unavailable, since May 01 2023.

5. All of Plaquemines Parish Water Works' meeting minutes or communications - including but not limited to memos, emails, notes, and analytical reports - regarding:
a. The effects of industrial and commercial users on water supply since 2020,
b. Venture Global's water use,
c. Venture Global's gifts, donations, and/or contributions to the Parish,
d. All communications which include representatives of Venture Global

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Delaney Nolan

title: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST – LICENSE PLATE READERS (Sacramento Police Department)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST – LICENSE PLATE READERS (Sacramento Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to request the following information from your office for the period January 1, 2020 to the date of this letter.

 - Number, if any, of License Plate Readers owned by this department or agency, including the manufacturer and whether a data storage package has been provided by the manufacturer.

 - Any documents or correspondence during the period encompassing this request regarding possible or planned acquisition of License Plate Readers.

 - Any existing or proposed usage policies regarding the use of License Plate Readers,  including protocols, training documents, data storage procedures and prohibited activities.

 - Any current or past litigation involving or referencing this department or agency involving the use of License Plate Readers.

Please notify me when this information is available.

Thank you for your attention to this request and for your prompt reply within 10 days.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aaron Swartz Day Police Surveillance Project

Sacramento Police Department ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #23-185: Date: April 20, 2023 Public Records Reference # 23-185 ​ Aaron Swartz, ​ This letter is in response to your California Public Records Act request dated February 27, 2023, wherein you requested "I am writing to request the following information from your office for the period January 1, 2020 to the date of this letter. - Number, if any, of License Plate Readers owned by this department or agency, including the manufacturer and whether a data storage package has been provided by the manufacturer. - Any documents or correspondence during the period encompassing this request regarding possible or planned acquisition of License Plate Readers. - Any existing or proposed usage policies regarding the use of License Plate Readers, including protocols, training documents, data storage procedures and prohibited activities. - Any current or past litigation involving or referencing this department or agency involving the use of License Plate Readers.". The Government Affairs Unit has identified records potentially responsive to your request and is continuing to compile additional records that may be responsive per Government Code 7920. Thank you,​ Sacramento Police Department Government Affairs Unit 5770 Freeport Blvd., Suite 100 Sacramento, CA 95822 ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? title: Donovan Day's Personnel File and Final Paycheck

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Donovan Day's Personnel File and Final Paycheck
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

1. A copy of Donovan Day's personnel file.
2. A copy of Donovan Day's final paycheck.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Carolyn

title: Heather Johnston Death - Police (Gwinnett County Sheriff)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Heather Johnston Death - Police (Gwinnett County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records, reports, body cam footage and other audio or video recordings related to the death of Heather Faye Besco Johnston. Mrs. Johnston died on or around July 3, 2021.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Cole Howard

communications.subject: The Missouri Sunshine Law Request: MO lobbyist expenditures
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the The Missouri Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

all lobbyist expenditures, dated from now to as far back as possible. I request the entire database, including all fields and any documentation necessary to interpret the data. If there are fields that you cannot release, please provide all other fields.

I can accept the data in many formats and on multiple media. I’d be happy to talk with your database administrator to figure out the best way to format the data.

If the fees for processing this request will exceed $40, please provide an itemized estimate of costs. If you choose to deny this request, please provide a written explanation for the denial, including a reference to the specific statutory exemption(s) upon which you rely.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

title: School Employees Data (City Of Orlando Public Record)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: School Employees Data (City Of Orlando Public Record)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Information on all teachers and educational administrators employed by the municipality. Including but not limited the following:

- first name
- last name
- middle name
- sex
- race (if available)
- date of birth
- date hired
- Assigned School
- Grade taught
- salary (if available)

If any of the information is unavailable please indicate and I will amend the request.

Please provide this in spreadsheet format covering the dates January, 1, 2010 to the present

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Sam

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Gabriel Kolko
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The FBI file of Gabriel Kolko, former History professor at the University of Pennsylvania. His obituary is available here:

https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/11/us/gabriel-kolko-left-leaning-historian-of-us-policy-dies-at-81.html

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

reemccarthy

title: Removal of bike lane on Arborway

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Removal of bike lane on Arborway
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

All documents (including emails, texts, and any other communications) concerning the repaving of Arborway, the redesign of Arborway, bike lanes on Arborway, or vehicle lanes on Arborway, sent on or after August 1 2023.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

George Schneeloch
